# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: single-cell-sequencing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The **cell** is the basic structural and functional unit of all forms of life or organisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The term comes from the Latin word *cellula* meaning 'small room'.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A biological cell basically consists of a semipermeable cell membrane enclosing cytoplasm that contains genetic material.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Most cells are only visible under a microscope.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Except for highly-differentiated cell types (examples include red blood cells and gametes) most cells are capable of replication, and protein synthesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cells emerged on Earth about four billion years ago.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All organisms are grouped into prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Prokaryotes are single-celled and include archaea and bacteria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Eukaryotes can be single-celled or multicellular.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Single-celled eukaryotes include most protists, some species of fungi (yeasts), and some species of algae.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Multicellular eukaryotes include animals, plants, some species of fungi, and some species of algae.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All multicellular organisms are made up of many different types of cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The diploid cells that make up the body of an animal or plant are known as somatic cells, which excludes the haploid gametes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Prokaryotes lack a membrane-bound nucleus and have a nucleoid instead.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In eukaryotic cells, the nucleus is enclosed in the nuclear membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Eukaryotic cells contain other membrane-bound organelles such as mitochondria, which provide energy for cell functions, and chloroplasts, in plants that create sugars by photosynthesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Other membrane-less organelles may be proteinaceous, such as the ribosomes present (though different) in both groups.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A unique membrane-bound prokaryotic organelle, the magnetosome has been discovered in magnetotactic bacteria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cells were discovered by Robert Hooke in 1665, who named them after their resemblance to cells in a monastery.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell theory, developed in 1839 by Matthias Jakob Schleiden and Theodor Schwann, states that all organisms are composed of one or more cells, that cells are the fundamental unit of structure and function in all organisms, and that all cells come from pre-existing cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Organisms are broadly grouped into eukaryotes and prokaryotes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Eukaryotic cells possess a membrane-bound nucleus, and prokaryotic cells lack a nucleus but have a nucleoid region.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Prokaryotes are single-celled organisms, whereas eukaryotes can be either single-celled or multicellular.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Single-celled eukaryotes include microalgae such as diatoms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Multicellular eukaryotes include all animals, and plants, most fungi, and some species of algae.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All prokaryotes are single-celled and include bacteria and archaea, two of the three domains of life.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Prokaryotic cells were likely the first form of life on Earth, characterized by having vital biological processes including cell signaling.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They are simpler and smaller than eukaryotic cells, lack a nucleus, and the other usually present membrane-bound organelles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Prokaryotic organelles are less complex, and are typically membrane-less.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All prokaryotic cells secrete different substances from their membranes, including exoenzymes, and extracellular polymeric substances.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Most prokaryotes are the smallest of all organisms, ranging from 0.1 to 5.0 μm in diameter.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The largest bacterium known, *Thiomargarita magnifica*, is visible to the naked eye with an average length of 1 cm, but can reach 2 cm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Bacteria are enclosed in a cell envelope, that protects the interior from the exterior.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It generally consists of a plasma membrane covered by a cell wall which, for some bacteria, is covered by a third layer, a gelatinous bacterial capsule.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The capsule may be polysaccharide as in pneumococci, meningococci or polypeptide as *Bacillus anthracis* or hyaluronic acid as in streptococci.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] *Mycoplasma* only possess the cell membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell envelope gives rigidity to the cell and separates the interior of the cell from its environment, serving as a protective mechanical and chemical filter.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell wall consists of peptidoglycan and acts as an additional barrier against exterior forces.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell wall acts to protect the cell mechanically and chemically from its environment, and is an additional layer of protection to the cell membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It also prevents the cell from expanding and bursting (cytolysis) from osmotic pressure due to a hypotonic environment.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The DNA of a bacterium typically consists of a single circular chromosome that is in direct contact with the cytoplasm in a region called the nucleoid.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Some bacteria contain multiple circular or even linear chromosomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cytoplasm also contains ribosomes and various inclusions where transcription takes place alongside translation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Extrachromosomal DNA as plasmids, are usually circular and encode additional genes, such as those of antibiotic resistance.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Linear bacterial plasmids have been identified in several species of spirochete bacteria, including species of *Borrelia* which causes Lyme disease.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The prokaryotic cytoskeleton in bacteria is involved in the maintenance of cell shape, polarity and cytokinesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Compartmentalization is a key feature of eukaryotic cells but some species of bacteria, have protein-based organelle-like microcompartments such as gas vesicles, and carboxysomes, and encapsulin nanocompartments.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Certain membrane-bound prokaryotic organelles have also been discovered.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They include the magnetosome of magnetotactic bacteria, and the anammoxosome of anammox bacteria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell-surface appendages can include flagella, and pili, protein structures that facilitate movement and communication between cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The flagellum stretches from the cytoplasm through the cell membrane and extrudes through the cell wall.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Fimbriae are short attachment pili, the other type of pilus is the longer conjugative type.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Fimbriae are formed of an antigenic protein called pilin, and are responsible for the attachment of bacteria to specific receptors on host cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Archaea are enclosed in a cell envelope consisting of a plasma membrane and a cell wall.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] An exception to this is the *Thermoplasma* that only has the cell membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell membranes of archaea are unique, consisting of ether-linked lipids.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The prokaryotic cytoskeleton has homologues of eukaryotic actin and tubulin.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A unique form of metabolism in the archaean is methanogenesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Their cell-surface appendage equivalent of the flagella is the differently structured and unique archaellum.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The DNA is contained in a circular chromosome in direct contact with the cytoplasm, in a region known as the nucleoid.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Ribosomes are also found freely in the cytoplasm, or attached to the cell membrane where DNA processing takes place.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The archaea are noted for their extremophile species, and many are selectively evolved to thrive in conditions of extreme heat, cold, acidity, alkalinity, or high salt.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A eukaryotic cell can be 2 to 100 times larger in diameter than a typical prokaryotic cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Eukaryotes can be single-celled, as in diatoms (microscopic algae), or microfungi such as yeasts, or multicellular, as in animals, plants, most fungi, and seaweed (macroalgae).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Multicellular organisms are made up of many different types of cell known overall as somatic cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Eukaryotes are distinguished by the presence of a membrane-bound nucleus that gives gives the eukaryote its name, which means "true nut" or "true kernel", where "nut" means the nucleus.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The nucleus is the largest membrane-bound organelle in the eukaryotic cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Other organelles present in all eukaryotic cells are the endoplasmic reticulum, ribosomes, the Golgi apparatus, mitochondria, lysosomes, peroxisomes, endosomes, and vesicles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The contents of the cell are contained within a cell membrane, and together with all the membranes of the organelles (except the mitochondria) are known as the endomembrane system.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All of these membranes are involved in the secretory and endocytic pathways, modifying, packaging, and transporting proteins and lipids to and from the trans Golgi network.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In mammalian cells, endocytosis includes early, late, and recycling endosomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Some eukaryotes cells including plant cells and fungi have a cell wall.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Plastids including chloroplasts feature mainly in plant cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] There are many cell variations among the different eukaryote groups.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Many cells project one or more cellular extensions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] And some organelles also project extensions such as stromules from plastids in plant cells, peroxules from peroxisomes, and matrixules from mitochondria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Most distinct cell types arise from a single totipotent cell, called a zygote, that differentiates into hundreds of different cell types during the course of development.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Differentiation of cells is driven by different environmental cues (such as cell–cell interaction) and intrinsic differences (such as those caused by the uneven distribution of molecules during division).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Eukaryotic cell types include those that make up animals, plants, fungi, algae, and protists.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All of which have many different species and cell differences.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A separate grouping of animals and fungi are known as opisthokonts.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] An eukaryotic cell has a cell membrane that surrounds a gel-like cytoplasm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cytoplasm contains the cytoskeleton, the cell nucleus, the endoplasmic reticulum, ribosomes, the Golgi apparatus, mitochondria, peroxisomes, endosomes, vacuoles and vesicles, and vaults.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A eukaryotic cell structure, includes an endomembrane system encompassing the cell membrane, and all the membranes of the organelles excluding those of the mitochondria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The whole system cooperates in the modification, packaging, and transport of proteins and lipids.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell membrane, or plasma membrane, is a selectively permeable membrane as an outer boundary of the cell that encloses the cytoplasm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Underlying, and attached to the cell membrane is the cell cortex, the outermost part of the actin cytoskeleton.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The membrane serves to separate and protect a cell from its surrounding environment and is made mostly from a lipid bilayer of phospholipids, which are amphiphilic (partly hydrophobic and partly hydrophilic).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It has been best described in the fluid mosaic model.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Embedded within the cell membrane are secretory macromolecular lipoprotein structures called porosomes; and a number of different channels and pumps involved in actively transporting molecules into and out of the cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The membrane is semi-permeable, and selectively permeable, in that it can either let a substance (molecule or ion) pass through freely, to a limited extent or not at all.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell surface receptors in the membrane allow cells to detect external signaling molecules such as hormones.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell membrane encloses the cytoplasm of the cell that surrounds all of the cell's organelles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It is made up of two main components, the cytoskeleton made up of protein filaments, and the cytosol.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The network of filaments and microtubules of the cytoskeleton gives shape and support to the cell, and has a part in organising the cell components.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cytosol is a gel-like substance made up of water, ions, and non-essential biomolecules, and is the main site of protein synthesis, and degradation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The acidity (pH) of the cytosol is near neutral, and is regulated by transporters in the cell membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Different proteins in the cytoplasm operate optimally at different pHs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cytosol forms 30%–50% of the cell's volume.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cytoskeleton acts to organize and maintain the cell's shape; anchors organelles in place; helps during endocytosis, and in the uptake of external materials by a cell.The cytoskeleton is composed of microtubules, intermediate filaments and microfilaments.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] There are a great number of proteins associated with them, each controlling a cell's structure by directing, bundling, and aligning filaments.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The outermost part of the cytoskeleton is the cell cortex, or actin cortex, a thin layer of cross-linked actomyosins.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Its thickness varies with cell type and physiology.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It directs the transport through the ER and the Golgi apparatus.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cytoskeleton in the animal cell also plays a part in cytokinesis, in the formation of the spindle apparatus during cell division, the separation of daughter cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Organelles are compartments of the cell that are specialized for carrying out one or more functions, analogous to the organs, such as the heart, and lungs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] There are several types of organelles held in the cytoplasm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Most organelles are membrane-bound, and vary in size and number based on the growth of the host cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Organelles include the nucleus, mitochondria, endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi apparatus, lysosomes, peroxisomes, vesicles, and vacuoles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Membrane-less organelles include the nucleolus in the nucleus, centrosomes, ribosomes, proteasomes, and vaults.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell nucleus is the largest organelle in the animal cells and many other eukaryotic cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It houses the cell's chromosomes, and is the place where almost all DNA replication and RNA synthesis (transcription) occur.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The nucleus is spherical and separated from the cytoplasm by a double-membraned nuclear envelope.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A space between the membranes is called the perinuclear space.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The nuclear envelope isolates and protects a cell's DNA from various molecules that could accidentally damage its structure or interfere with its processing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] During processing, DNA is transcribed, or copied into a special RNA, called messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This mRNA is then transported out of the nucleus, where it is translated into a specific protein molecule.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The nucleolus is a specialized biomolecular condensate within the nucleus where ribosome subunits are assembled.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It is one of several types of membrane-less nuclear bodies.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cells use DNA for their long-term information storage that is encoded in its DNA sequence.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] RNA is used for information transport (e.g., mRNA) and enzymatic functions (e.g., ribosomal RNA).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules are used to add amino acids during protein translation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The DNA of each cell is its genetic material, and is organized in multiple linear molecules, called chromosomes, that are coiled around histone proteins and housed in the cell nucleus.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In humans, the nuclear genome is divided into 46 linear chromosomes, including 22 homologous chromosome pairs and a pair of sex chromosomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The nucleus is a membrane-bound organelle.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The endoplasmic reticulum (ER) is a transport network for molecules targeted for certain modifications and specific destinations, as compared to molecules that float freely in the cytoplasm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The ER has two forms: the rough endoplasmic reticulum (RER), which has ribosomes on its surface that secrete proteins into the ER, and the smooth endoplasmic reticulum (SER), which lacks ribosomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The smooth ER plays a role in calcium sequestration and release, and helps in synthesis of lipid.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The Golgi apparatus processes and packages proteins, and lipids, that are synthesized by the cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It is organized as a stack of plate-like structures known as cisternae.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Mitochondria are self-replicating double membrane-bound organelles that occur in various numbers, shapes, and sizes in the cytoplasm of the cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Aerobic respiration in the mitochondria generates the cell's energy by oxidative phosphorylation, using oxygen to release energy stored in cellular nutrients (typically pertaining to glucose) to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Mitochondria are descended from bacteria that formed an endosymbiotic relationship with ancient prokaryotes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Mitochondria multiply by binary fission and have their own DNA contained in multiple small circular chromosomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) is very small compared to nuclear DNA, but it codes for 13 proteins involved in mitochondrial energy production and specific transfer RNAs (tRNAs).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Mitochondria also have their own ribosomes known as mitoribosomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A lysosome is the most acidic compartment in the cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It contains over 60 different hydrolytic enzymes that need an acidic environment.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They digest excess or worn-out organelles, food particles, and engulfed viruses or bacteria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell could not house these destructive enzymes if they were not contained in a membrane-bound compartment.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Peroxisomes are microbodies bounded by a single membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A peroxisome has no DNA or ribosomes and the proteins that it needs are encoded in the nucleus, and selectively imported from the cytosol.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Some proteins enter via the endomembrane reticulum.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They have enzymes that rid the cell of toxic peroxides.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The enzymatic content of the peroxisomes varies widely across the species, as it can in an individual organism.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The peroxisomes in animal cells are concentrated in the liver cells and adipocytes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Some cells, most notably *Amoeba*, have contractile vacuoles, which can pump water out of the cell if there is too much water.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A ribosome is a large complex of RNA and protein molecules considered as a membrane-less organelle when freely found in the cytosol, or as a membrane-bound organelle when located in the rough type of endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They each consist of two subunits, one larger than the other, and act as an assembly line where messenger RNA from the nucleus is used to synthesise proteins from amino acids.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A vault is a large ribonuclear protein particle, a membrane-less organelle, three times the size of a ribosome but with only three proteins in contrast to the near hundred in the ribosome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Most human cells have around 10,000 vaults, and in some types of immune cell there may be up to 100,000.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Macrophages have the greatest number of vaults of any human cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Vaults are largely overlooked because their functions are purely speculative.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They may play a role in transport from the nucleus to the cytoplasm, and may serve as scaffolds for signal transduction proteins.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They are present in normal tissues, and more so in secretory and excretory epithelial cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Proteasomes are intricate membrane-less protein complexes responsible for the degradation of regulatory proteins, and damaged proteins in the cytosol and nucleus.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] They also function in protein homeostasis, stress response, and in the control of cell division and signal transduction.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All the cells in an animal body develop from one totipotent diploid cell called a zygote.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] During the embryonic development of an animal, the cells differentiate into the specialised tissues and organs of the organism.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Different groups of cells differentiate from the germ layers.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Some other animals known as diploblasts have two germ layers the ectoderm, and the endoderm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] More advanced animals have an extra layer, the middle mesodermal layer, and are known as triploblastic.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Triploblastic animals make up the large clade of Bilateria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Differentiation results in structural or functional changes to stem cells, and progenitor cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The ectoderm gives rise to several different types of epithelial tissues including the skin, and glands, and to the nervous tissue.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Epithelium as mesothelium forms the lining of many organs, and inner cavities.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Epithelial cells are joined together in sheets by way of cell junctions; adherens junctions, and desmosomes bind the cells together, and hemidesmosomes bind the cells to the basement membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All three types are linked to the cell cytoskeleton.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] There are an estimated 200 different cell types in the human body.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The estimated cell count in a typical adult human body is around 30 trillion cells, 36 trillion in an adult male, and 28 trillion in a female.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Like other eukaryotic cells, animal cells are made up of a cell membrane containing a gel like cytoplasm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The centrosome is a membrane-less organelle composed of pericentriolar material and the two centrioles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The centrosome is the main microtubule organizing center in the animal cell that produces the microtubules key components of the cytoskeleton.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Centrosomes are composed of two centrioles which lie perpendicular to each other in which each has an organization like a cartwheel, which separate during cell division and help in the formation of the mitotic spindle.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] While most other eukaryotes due have centrioles, plants do not and centrosomes are unique to animal cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Some types of specialized cell are localized to a particular animal group.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Vertebrates for example have specialized, structurally changed cells including muscle cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell membrane of a skeletal muscle cell or of a cardiac muscle cell is termed the sarcolemma.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] And the cytoplasm is termed the sarcoplasm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Skeletal muscle cells also become multinucleated.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Populations of animal groups evolve to become distinct species, where sexual reproduction is isolated.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The many species of vertebrates for example have other unique characteristics by way of additional specialized cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In some species of electric fish for example modified muscle cells or nerve cells have specialized to become electerocytes capable of creating and storing electrical energy for future release, as in stunning prey, or use in electrolocation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] These are large flat cells in the electric eel, and electric ray in which thousands are stacked into an electric organ comparable to a voltaic pile.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Many animal cells are ciliated and most cells except red blood cells have primary cilia.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Primary cilia play important roles in chemosensation and mechanosensation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In the reproductive system ciliated epithelium in the fallopian tubes move the egg from the uterus to the ovary.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Motile cilia also known as flagella, drive the sperm cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Invertebrate planarians have ciliated excretory flame cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Other excretory cells also found in planarians are solenocytes that are long and flagellated.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Plant cells have cell walls composed of cellulose, hemicelluloses, and pectin that are constructed outside the cell membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In sclerenchyma tissue lignin is secreted to form a secondary wall inside the primary cell wall.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cutin is secreted outside the primary cell wall and into the outer layers of the secondary cell wall of the epidermal cells of leaves, stems and other above-ground organs to form the plant cuticle.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell walls perform many essential functions, they provide shape to form the tissue and organs of the plant, and play an important role in intercellular communication and plant-microbe interactions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Specialized cell-to-cell communication pathways known as plasmodesmata, occur in the form of pores in the primary cell wall through which the cell membrane and endoplasmic reticulum of adjacent cells are continuous.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Organelles in plant cells, include pigment-containing plastids, especially chloroplasts that contain chlorophyll (also found in algae), large water-storage vacuoles, and two types of peroxisome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Chloroplasts capture the sun's energy to make carbohydrates through photosynthesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Chromoplasts contain fat-soluble carotenoid pigments such as orange carotene and yellow xanthophylls which helps in synthesis and storage.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Leucoplasts are non-pigmented plastids and helps in storage of nutrients.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The vacuoles are larger than those in animal cells, and their membrane transports ions against concentration gradients.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] One type of peroxisome is in the leaves where it takes part in photorespiration.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The other type is in germinating seeds where it takes part in the conversion of fatty acids into sugars for the plant's growth.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In this peroxisome type the enzymatic content is so different from other groups that it has an alternative name of glyoxysome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The enzymes are of the glyoxylate cycle.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The plant cytoskeleton is a dynamic structure that has a scaffold of microtubules and microfilaments, but no intermediate filaments.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The microtubule organizing center in plant cells is often sited underneath the cell membrane where nucleated microtubules often form sheet-like semi-parallel arrays.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Plant hormones are produced by all plant cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Different hormones act as signaling molecules to control all aspects of the plant's growth and development including embryogenesis and reproduction, and in pathogen defense.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Algae members are photoautotrophs able to use photosynthesis to produce energy.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In eukaryotes, photosynthesis is made possible by the use of plastids, organelles in the cytoplasm known as chloroplasts.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Photosynthesis is found in both prokaryotic cyanobacteria and multiple clades of eukaryotic algae; red algae, brown algae, and green algae, which are closely related to land plants.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Alginate is a polysaccharide found in the matrix of the cell walls of brown algae, and has many important uses in the food industry, and in pharmacology.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cells of fungi have in addition to the shared eukaryotic organelles a spitzenkörper in their endomembrane system, associated with hyphal tip growth.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It is a phase-dark body that is composed of an aggregation of membrane-bound vesicles containing cell wall components, serving as a point of assemblage and release of such components intermediate between the Golgi and the cell membrane.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The spitzenkörper is motile and generates new hyphal tip growth as it moves forward.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cell walls of fungi are uniquely made of a chitin-glucan complex.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Chloroplasts are not found in fungal cells, their pigments are instead associated with their cell walls.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The cells of protists may be bounded only by a cell membrane, or may in addition have a cell wall, or may be covered by a pellicle (in ciliates), a test (in testate amoebae), or a frustule (in diatoms).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Some protists such as amoebae may feed on other organisms and ingest food by phagocytosis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Vacuoles known as phagosomes in the cytoplasm may be used to draw in and incorporate the captured particles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Other types of protists are photoautotrophs, providing themselves with energy by photosynthesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Most single-celled protists are motile, and generate movement with cilia, flagella, or pseudopodia.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Ciliates have two different sorts of nuclei: a tiny, diploid micronucleus (the "generative nucleus", which carries the germline of the cell), and a large, ampliploid macronucleus (the "vegetative nucleus", which takes care of general cell regulation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] During cell division, a single cell, the *mother cell* divides into two daughter cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This leads to the growth of tissue in multicellular organisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Prokaryotic cells divide by binary fission, while eukaryotic cells usually undergo a process of nuclear division, called mitosis, followed by division of the cell, called cytokinesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A diploid cell may undergo meiosis to produce haploid cells, usually four.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Haploid cells serve as gametes in multicellular organisms, fusing to form new diploid cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] DNA replication, or the process of duplicating a cell's genome, always happens when a cell divides through mitosis or binary fission.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This occurs during the S (synthesis) phase of the cell cycle.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In meiosis, the DNA is replicated only once, while the cell divides twice.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] DNA replication only occurs before meiosis I.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] DNA replication does not occur when the cells divide the second time, in meiosis II.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Replication, like all cellular activities, requires specialized proteins.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell signaling is the process by which a cell interacts with itself, other cells, and the environment.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Typically, the signaling process involves three components: the first messenger (the ligand), the receptor, and the signal itself.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Most cell signaling is chemical in nature, and can occur with neighboring cells or more distant targets.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Signal receptors are complex proteins or tightly bound multimer of proteins, located in the plasma membrane or within the interior.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Each cell is programmed to respond to specific extracellular signal molecules, and this process is the basis of development, tissue repair, immunity, and homeostasis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Individual cells are able to manage receptor sensitivity including turning them off, and receptors can become less sensitive when they are occupied for long durations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Errors in signaling interactions may cause diseases such as cancer, autoimmunity, and diabetes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Protein targeting or protein sorting is the biological mechanism by which proteins are transported to their appropriate destinations within or outside the cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Proteins can be targeted to the inner space of an organelle, different intracellular membranes, the plasma membrane, or to the exterior of the cell via secretion.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Information contained in the protein itself directs this delivery process.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Correct sorting is crucial for the cell; errors or dysfunction in sorting have been linked to multiple diseases.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] All cells contain enzyme systems that scan for DNA damage and carry out repair.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Diverse repair processes have evolved in all organisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Repair is vital to maintain DNA integrity, avoid cell death and errors of replication that could lead to mutation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Repair processes include nucleotide excision repair, DNA mismatch repair, non-homologous end joining of double-strand breaks, recombinational repair and light-dependent repair (photoreactivation).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Between successive cell divisions, cells grow through the functioning of cellular metabolism.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell metabolism is the process by which individual cells process nutrient molecules.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Metabolism has two distinct divisions: catabolism, in which the cell breaks down complex molecules to produce energy and reducing power, and anabolism, in which the cell uses energy and reducing power to construct complex molecules and perform other biological functions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Complex sugars can be broken down into simpler sugar molecules called monosaccharides such as glucose.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Once inside the cell, glucose is broken down to make adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a molecule that possesses readily available energy, through two different pathways.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In plant cells, chloroplasts create sugars by photosynthesis, using the energy of light to join molecules of water and carbon dioxide.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cells are capable of synthesizing new proteins, which are essential for the modulation and maintenance of cellular activities.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This process involves the formation of new protein molecules from amino acid building blocks based on information encoded in DNA/RNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Protein synthesis generally consists of two major steps: transcription and translation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Transcription is the process where genetic information in DNA is used to produce a complementary RNA strand.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This RNA strand is then processed to give messenger RNA (mRNA), which is free to migrate into the cytoplasm. mRNA molecules bind to protein-RNA complexes called ribosomes located in the cytosol, where they are translated into polypeptide sequences.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The ribosome mediates the formation of a polypeptide sequence based on the mRNA sequence.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The mRNA sequence directly relates to the polypeptide sequence by binding to transfer RNA (tRNA) adapter molecules in binding pockets within the ribosome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The new polypeptide chain then folds into a functional three-dimensional protein molecule.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Unicellular organisms can move in order to find food or escape predators.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Common mechanisms of motion include flagella and cilia, and the projection of pseudopodia in amoeboid movement.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cells in multicellular organisms can move during processes such as wound healing, the immune response, and cancer metastasis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In wound healing in animals, white blood cells move to the wound site to kill the pathogens causing infection.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell motility involves many receptors, crosslinking, bundling, binding, adhesion, motor and other proteins.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The process is divided into three steps: protrusion of the leading edge of the cell, adhesion of the leading edge and de-adhesion at the cell body and rear, and cytoskeletal contraction to pull the cell forward.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Each step is driven by physical forces generated by unique segments of the cytoskeleton.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cell death occurs when a cell ceases to carry out its functions, as a result of ageing, or types of cell injury (necrosis).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Programmed cell death, including apoptosis, and autophagy is a natural process of replacing dead cells with new ones.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A separate mode of cellular death is known as a mitotic catastrophe, which occurs during mitosis, following the improper progression of, or entrance to the cell cycle.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This mechanism operates to prevent genomic instability.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Other cell death pathways are described, and include anoikis, pyroptosis, mitoptosis, parthanatos, and necroptosis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The origin of cells has to do with the origin of life, which began the history of life on Earth.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Small molecules needed for life may have been carried to Earth on meteorites, created at deep-sea hydrothermal vents, or synthesized by lightning in a reducing atmosphere.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] There is little experimental data defining what the first self-replicating forms were.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] RNA may have been the earliest self-replicating molecule, as it can both store genetic information and catalyze chemical reactions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This process required an enzyme to catalyze the RNA reactions, which may have been the early peptides that formed in hydrothermal vents.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cells emerged around 4 billion years ago.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The first cells were most likely heterotrophs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The early cell membranes were probably simpler and more permeable than later ones, with only a single fatty acid chain per lipid.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Lipids spontaneously form bilayered vesicles in water, and could have preceded RNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Eukaryotic cells were created some 2.2 billion years ago in a process called eukaryogenesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This is widely agreed to have involved symbiogenesis, in which an archaean and a bacterium came together to create the first eukaryotic common ancestor.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It evolved into a population of single-celled organisms that included the last eukaryotic common ancestor, gaining capabilities along the way.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This cell had a new level of complexity, with a nucleus and facultatively aerobic mitochondria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] It featured at least one centriole and cilium, sex (meiosis and syngamy), peroxisomes, and a dormant cyst with a cell wall of chitin and/or cellulose.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The last eukaryotic common ancestor gave rise to the eukaryotes' crown group, containing the ancestors of animals, fungi, plants, and a diverse range of single-celled organisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The green plants were created around 1.6 billion years ago with a second episode of symbiogenesis that added chloroplasts, derived from cyanobacteria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Multicellular behavior is demonstrated by microorganisms that are cloned from a single cell and form visible microbial colonies.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] A microbial consortium of two or more species can form a biofilm by the secretion of extracellular polymeric substances (EPSs).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Slime molds consist of different groups of microorganisms grouped together in a multicellular-like fashion.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The first evidence of multicellularity in an organism comes from cyanobacteria-like organisms that lived between 3 and 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Cyanobacteria are variable in morphology, filamentous forms exhibit functional cell differentiation such as heterocysts (for nitrogen fixation), akinetes (resting stage cells), and hormogonia (reproductive, motile filaments).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] These, together with the intercellular connections they possess, are considered the first signs of multicellularity.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Multicellularity was made possible by the development of the extracellular matrix (ECM) similar in function to the bacterial EPS that consists of extracellular polymeric substances.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] EPS enables microbial cell adhesion, and is believed to be the first evolutionary step toward multicellular organisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Basement membranes are a type of specialized extracellular matrix that surrounds most animal tissues, and are essential in their formation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] Extracellular matrix components of laminin domains, integrated with other proteins such as cadherins have been described in single-celled motile choanoflagellates that pre-dates the evolutionary emergence of basement membranes, one of the two types of ECM.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The emergence of the basement membrane coincided with the origin of multicellularity.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The other type of ECM is the interstial matrix.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] The evolution of multicellularity from unicellular ancestors has been replicated in the laboratory, in evolution experiments using predation as the selective pressure.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] In 1665, Robert Hooke examined a thin slice of cork under his microscope, and saw a structure of small enclosures.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] He wrote "I could exceeding plainly perceive it to be all perforated and porous, much like a honeycomb, but that the pores of it were not regular".
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] To further support his theory, Matthias Schleiden and Theodor Schwann studied cells of both animal and plants.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] What they discovered were significant differences between the two types of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cell-biology] This put forth the idea that cells were fundamental to both plants and animals.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Most cellular deconvolution algorithms consider an input data in a form of a matrix $X_{m\times n}$ , which represents some molecular information (e.g. gene expression data or DNA methylation data) measured over a group of n samples and m marks (e.g. genes or CpG sites).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] The goal of the algorithm is to use these data and return an output matrix $W_{k\times n}$ , representing the proportions of k distinct cell types in each of the n samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Some methods limit the sum of each column of W matrix less than or equal to one, so that the proportions of cell types sum up to the overall number of cells in the sample (less than one when there are some unknown cell types in the samples).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Moreover, it is assumed that the values of W matrix are non-negative as they pertain to proportions of cell types.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] There are two broad categories of methods aiming at estimating the proportion of cell types in samples using some type of omics data (bulk gene expression or DNA methylation data).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] A reference matrix can be represented by a matrix $H_{m\times k}$ , representing the expected value for m markers (genes or CpG sites) for each of k cell types known to be presented in the samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] These references can be derived by exploring external single-cell epigenomics or transcriptomics datasets generated for a group of samples similar (e.g. in terms of biological condition, sex and age) to the samples for which the deconvolution method will be applied.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] These methods use statistical approaches such as non-negative or constrained linear regression methods to dissect the contribution of each cell type to the aggregated bulk signals of genes or CpG sites.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Constrained regression is the basis for many of reference-free cellular deconvolution methods existing in the literature, aiming at estimating the cell proportion values ( $W_{k\times n}$ ) that maximizes the similarity between $HW^{T}$ and X .
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] The performance of reference-based methods depends critically on the quality of the reference profiles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] There are a variety of approaches for isolating different cell types to measure their gene expression or DNA methylation levels to be used as references in the deconvolution algorithms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Earlier methods used cell sorting methods such as FACS (fluorescence-activated cell sorting) based on the flow cytometry technique, which separates the populations of cells belonging to different cell types based on their cell sizes, morphologies (shape), and surface protein expressions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] With the advance in single-cell technologies, newer approaches started to incorporate references for cell-types measured on a single-cell resolution obtained for a subset of subjects in the study or external subjects from a similar biological condition.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Reference-free methods do not need the reference profiles of cell-type specific genes (or CpGs), although they might still require the identity (name) of cell-type-specific genes (or CpGs).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] These methods might be considered as a modification of reference-based methods where **both** H and W are unknown, and the goal is to jointly estimate both matrices so that the similarity between $HW^{T}$ and X is maximized.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Many of the reference-free methods are based on mathematical framework of non-negative matrix factorization, which imposes a non-negativity constraint on the elements of H and W .
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Additional constraints such as the assumption of orthogonality between the columns of H might be incorporated to improve the interpretability of results and prevent overfitting.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] The advance of single-cell technologies enables the profiling of each individual cell in a sample, which help elucidate the issue of cellular heterogeneity by measuring the proportions of different cells in samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Even though the quality of single cell profiling technologies has been on the rise in recent years, these technologies are still costly, limiting their applications in large populations of samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Single cell technologies such as single cell transcriptomic methods also tend to have higher error rates due to factors such as high dropout events.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] There are large amounts of old bulk data, such as microarray, from studies concerning various diseases and biological conditions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] These datasets could be considered important resources in studying of rare disease, long follow-up studies or samples and tissues that are difficult to extract.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] In addition, this can also improve the statistical power by combining similar datasets.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Since the biological samples for many of these studies are not available or accessible anymore, reprofiling the data using single cell technologies might not be within the realm of possibilities for many studies.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Invention of more advanced cellular deconvolution methods gives the opportunity to researchers to come back to old omics studies, reanalyze their datasets, and scrutinize their findings.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Reference-based approaches rely on the availability of accurate references to estimate cell proportions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] The discrepancy between the biology of the samples underlying the references and the samples for which the cell proportions are being estimated could introduce bias in estimated cell proportions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Studies have shown that using references obtained from samples with different phenotypes such as age, gender, and disease status than the population of interest reduces the performance of reference-based methods to levels lower than their reference-free counterparts.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Reference-based approaches assume the existence of prior knowledge on the types of cells existing in a sample.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Therefore, these methods may fail to perform accurately when the data includes rare or otherwise unknown cell types with no references incorporated in the algorithm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] For example, cancer tumors consist of heterogeneous mixtures of various healthy cells of different types such as immune cells and cells related to affected tissues in addition to tumor cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Although it might be possible to provide references for the immune cells, we do not usually have access to references or signatures for cancer cells due to the unique patterns of mutations and distributions of molecular information in each individual.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] These situations have been addressed in some studies under the label of deconvolution methods with partial reference availability.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Studies have shown that the proportions of different cell types might show correlations with various phenotypes such as different diseases.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] For example, the proportions of Parathyroid oxyphil cells in the samples collected from the parathyroid gland for groups of patients show a significant correlation with the presence of clinical characteristics of chronic kidney disease (CKD).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Another study applying the cellular deconvolution algorithms to gene expression data of Alzheimer's patients find that patients with lower proportions of neuronal cells in the samples collected from their cerebral cortex are more likely to show the clinical characteristics of dementia.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Cellular deconvolution algorithms could enable researchers to investigate the interactions between cell proportions and various diseases or biological phenotypes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Since the proportions of cell types in samples vary and might show significant correlations with the disease or phenotype of interest, these correlations may confound the functional relationships between genes or CpG sites and the disease or phenotypes under study.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] For example, studies aimed at finding genes involved in Alzheimer's disease may end up selecting genes that are exclusively expressed in neurons and therefore have lower expression levels in Alzheimer's patients due to compositional changes of cell types during neurodegeneration.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/cellular-deconvolution] Such genes are not actionable targets for the treatment of Alzheimer's since they are not causally involved in the biological mechanism underlying Alzheimer's disease, but are only brought up by the confounding effects of cell types.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Typically microfluidic systems transport, mix, separate, or otherwise process fluids.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Various applications rely on passive fluid control using capillary forces, in the form of capillary flow modifying elements, akin to flow resistors and flow accelerators.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In some applications, external actuation means are additionally used for a directed transport of the media.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Examples are rotary drives applying centrifugal forces for the fluid transport on the passive chips.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] *Active microfluidics* refers to the defined manipulation of the working fluid by active (micro) components such as micropumps or microvalves.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Micropumps supply fluids in a continuous manner or are used for dosing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microvalves determine the flow direction or the mode of movement of pumped liquids.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Often, processes normally carried out in a lab are miniaturised on a single chip, which enhances efficiency and mobility, and reduces sample and reagent volumes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The behaviour of fluids at the microscale can differ from "macrofluidic" behaviour in that factors such as surface tension, energy dissipation, and fluidic resistance start to dominate the system, as opposed to inertial effects.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidics studies how these behaviours change, and how they can be worked around, or exploited for new uses.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] At small scales (channel size of around 100 nanometers to 500 micrometers) some unintuitive properties appear.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In particular, the Reynolds number (which compares the effect of the momentum of a fluid to the effect of viscosity) can become very low.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] One consequence is co-flowing fluids do not necessarily mix in the traditional sense, as flow becomes laminar rather than turbulent; molecular transport between them must often be through diffusion.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] High specificity of chemical and physical properties (concentration, pH, temperature, shear force, etc.) can also be ensured resulting in more uniform reaction conditions and higher grade products in single and multi-step reactions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic flows need only be constrained by geometrical length scale – the modalities and methods used to achieve such a geometrical constraint are highly dependent on the targeted application.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Traditionally, microfluidic flows have been generated inside closed channels with the channel cross section being in the order of 10 μm x 10 μm.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Each of these methods has its own associated techniques to maintain robust fluid flow which have matured over several years.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The behavior of fluids and their control in open microchannels came into focus around 2005 and applied in air-to-liquid sample collection and chromatography.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In open microfluidics, at least one boundary of the system is removed, exposing the fluid to air or another interface (i.e. liquid).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Advantages of open microfluidics include accessibility to the flowing liquid for intervention, larger liquid-gas surface area, and minimized bubble formation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Another advantage of open microfluidics is the ability to integrate open systems with surface-tension driven fluid flow, which eliminates the need for external pumping methods such as peristaltic or syringe pumps.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Open microfluidic devices are also easy and inexpensive to fabricate by milling, thermoforming, and hot embossing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In addition, open microfluidics eliminates the need to glue or bond a cover for devices, which could be detrimental to capillary flows.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Examples of open microfluidics include open-channel microfluidics, rail-based microfluidics, paper-based, and thread-based microfluidics.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Disadvantages to open systems include susceptibility to evaporation, contamination, and limited flow rate.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Continuous flow microfluidics rely on the control of a steady state liquid flow through narrow channels or porous media predominantly by accelerating or hindering fluid flow in capillary elements.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In paper based microfluidics, capillary elements can be achieved through the simple variation of section geometry.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In general, the actuation of liquid flow is implemented either by external pressure sources, external mechanical pumps, integrated mechanical micropumps, or by combinations of capillary forces and electrokinetic mechanisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Continuous-flow microfluidic operation is the mainstream approach because it is easy to implement and less sensitive to protein fouling problems.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Continuous-flow devices are adequate for many well-defined and simple biochemical applications, and for certain tasks such as chemical separation, but they are less suitable for tasks requiring a high degree of flexibility or fluid manipulations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] These closed-channel systems are inherently difficult to integrate and scale because the parameters that govern flow field vary along the flow path making the fluid flow at any one location dependent on the properties of the entire system.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Permanently etched microstructures also lead to limited reconfigurability and poor fault tolerance capability.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Process monitoring capabilities in continuous-flow systems can be achieved with highly sensitive microfluidic flow sensors based on MEMS technology, which offers resolutions down to the nanoliter range.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Droplet-based microfluidics is differs from continuous microfluidics; droplet-based microfluidics manipulates discrete volumes of fluids in immiscible phases with low Reynolds number and laminar flow regimes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Interest in droplet-based microfluidics systems has been growing substantially in past decades.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microdroplets allow for handling miniature volumes (μL to fL) of fluids conveniently, provide better mixing, encapsulation, sorting, and sensing, and suit high throughput experiments.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Exploiting the benefits of droplet-based microfluidics efficiently requires a deep understanding of droplet generation to perform various logical operations such as droplet manipulation, droplet sorting, droplet merging, and droplet breakup.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Alternatives to the above closed-channel continuous-flow systems include novel open structures, where discrete, independently controllable droplets are manipulated on a substrate using electrowetting.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Following the analogy of digital microelectronics, this approach is referred to as digital microfluidics.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Le Pesant et al. pioneered the use of electrocapillary forces to move droplets on a digital track.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The "fluid transistor" pioneered by Cytonix also played a role.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The technology was subsequently commercialised by Duke University.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] By using discrete unit-volume droplets, a microfluidic function can be reduced to a set of repeated basic operations, i.e., moving one unit of fluid over one unit of distance.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This "digitisation" method facilitates the use of a hierarchical and cell-based approach for microfluidic biochip design.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Therefore, digital microfluidics offers a flexible and scalable system architecture as well as high fault-tolerance capability.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Moreover, because each droplet can be controlled independently, these systems also have dynamic reconfigurability, whereby groups of unit cells in a microfluidic array can be reconfigured to change their functionality during the concurrent execution of a set of bioassays.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Although droplets are manipulated in confined microfluidic channels, since the control on droplets is not independent, it should not be confused as "digital microfluidics".
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] One common actuation method for digital microfluidics is electrowetting-on-dielectric (EWOD).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Many lab-on-a-chip applications have been demonstrated within the digital microfluidics paradigm using electrowetting.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Paper-based microfluidic devices are proposed to provide portable, cheap, and user-friendly medical diagnostic systems.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Paper based microfluidics rely on the phenomenon of capillary penetration in porous media.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] To tune fluid penetration in porous substrates such as paper in two and three dimensions, the pore structure, wettability and geometry of the microfluidic devices can be controlled while the viscosity and evaporation rate of the liquid play a further significant role.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Many such devices feature hydrophobic barriers on hydrophilic paper that passively transport aqueous solutions to outlets where biological reactions take place.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Paper-based microfluidics are considered as portable point-of-care biosensors used in a remote setting where advanced medical diagnostic tools are not accessible.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Current applications include portable glucose detection and environmental testing, with hopes of reaching areas that lack advanced medical diagnostic tools.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] One potential application area involves particle detection in fluids.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The physics behind this is relatively simple, described in a classic paper by DeBlois and Bean, and the implementation first described in Coulter's original patent.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This is the method used to e.g. size and count erythrocytes (red blood cells) as well as leukocytes (white blood cells) for standard blood analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The generic term for this method is resistive pulse sensing (RPS); Coulter counting is a trademark term.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] However, the RPS method does not work well for particles below 1 μm diameter, as the signal-to-noise ratio falls below the reliably detectable limit, set mostly by the size of the pore in which the analyte passes and the input noise of the first-stage amplifier.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The limit on the pore size in traditional RPS Coulter counters is set by the method used to make the pores, which while a trade secret, most likely uses traditional mechanical methods.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This is where microfluidics can have an impact: The lithography-based production of microfluidic devices, or more likely the production of reusable molds for making microfluidic devices using a molding process, is limited to sizes much smaller than traditional machining.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Critical dimensions down to 1 μm are easily fabricated, and with a bit more effort and expense, feature sizes below 100 nm can be patterned reliably as well.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This enables the inexpensive production of pores integrated in a microfluidic circuit where the pore diameters can reach sizes of order 100 nm, with a concomitant reduction in the minimum particle diameters by several orders of magnitude.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] As a result, there has been some university-based development of microfluidic particle counting and sizing with the accompanying commercialization of this technology.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This method has been termed microfluidic resistive pulse sensing (MRPS).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] One application for microfluidic devices is the separation and sorting of different fluids or cell types.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic devices have been integrated with magnetophoresis: the migration of particles by a magnetic field.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This can be accomplished by sending a fluid containing at least one magnetic component through a microfluidic channel that has a magnet positioned along the length of the channel.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This creates a magnetic field inside the microfluidic channel which draws magnetically active substances towards it, effectively separating the magnetic and non-magnetic components of the fluid.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This technique can be readily utilized in industrial settings where the fluid at hand already contains magnetically active material.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] For example, a handful of metallic impurities can find their way into certain consumable liquids, namely milk and other dairy products.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Conveniently, in the case of milk, many of these metal contaminants exhibit paramagnetism.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Therefore, before packaging, milk can be flowed through channels with magnetic gradients as a means of purifying out the metal contaminants.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] cell separations are of interest in microfluidics.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] First, a paramagnetic substance (usually micro/nanoparticles or a paramagnetic fluid) needs to be functionalized to target the cell type of interest.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This can be accomplished by identifying a transmembranal protein unique to the cell type of interest and subsequently functionalizing magnetic particles with the complementary antigen or antibody.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Once the magnetic particles are functionalized, they are dispersed in a cell mixture where they bind to only the cells of interest.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The resulting cell/particle mixture can then be flowed through a microfluidic device with a magnetic field to separate the targeted cells from the rest.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Conversely, microfluidic-assisted magnetophoresis may be used to facilitate efficient mixing within microdroplets or plugs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] To accomplish this, microdroplets are injected with paramagnetic nanoparticles and are flowed through a straight channel which passes through rapidly alternating magnetic fields.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This causes the magnetic particles to be quickly pushed from side to side within the droplet and results in the mixing of the microdroplet contents.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This eliminates the need for tedious engineering considerations that are necessary for traditional, channel-based droplet mixing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Other research has also shown that the label-free separation of cells may be possible by suspending cells in a paramagnetic fluid and taking advantage of the magneto-Archimedes effect.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] While this does eliminate the complexity of particle functionalization, more research is needed to fully understand the magneto-Archimedes phenomenon and how it can be used to this end.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This is not an exhaustive list of the various applications of microfluidic-assisted magnetophoresis; the above examples merely highlight the versatility of this separation technique in both current and future applications.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic structures include micropneumatic systems, i.e. microsystems for the handling of off-chip fluids (liquid pumps, gas valves, etc.), and microfluidic structures for the on-chip handling of nanoliter (nl) and picoliter (pl) volumes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] To date, the most successful commercial application of microfluidics is the inkjet printhead.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Additionally, microfluidic manufacturing advances mean that makers can produce the devices in low-cost plastics such as polymethymethacrylate (PMMA), polystyrene, cyclic olefin polymer (COP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC) and automatically verify part quality.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic devices are often first produced using fabrication methods such as soft lithography, micro milling or laser machining to validate microchannel designs before transitioning to scalable thermoplastic manufacturing processes such as injection molding.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Advances in microfluidics technology promise to improve molecular biology procedures for enzymatic analysis (e.g., glucose and lactate assays), DNA analysis (e.g., polymerase chain reaction and high-throughput sequencing), proteomics, and in chemical synthesis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic biochips integrate assay operations such as detection, with sample pre-treatment and sample preparation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] A promising application area for biochips is clinical pathology, especially the point-of-care diagnosis of diseases.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In addition, microfluidics-based devices, capable of continuous sampling and real-time testing of air/water samples for biochemical toxins and other dangerous pathogens, can serve as an always-on "bio-smoke alarm" for early warning.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic technology has provide tools for biologists to control the cellular environment.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Early biochips were based on the idea of a DNA microarray, e.g., the GeneChip DNAarray from Affymetrix, which is a piece of glass, plastic or silicon substrate, on which pieces of DNA (probes) are affixed in a microscopic array.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Similar to a DNA microarray, a protein array is a miniature array where a multitude of different capture agents, most frequently monoclonal antibodies, are deposited on a chip surface; they are used to determine the presence and/or amount of proteins in biological samples, e.g., blood.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] A drawback of DNA and protein arrays is that they are neither reconfigurable nor scalable after manufacture.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Digital microfluidics has been described as a means for carrying out Digital PCR.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In addition to microarrays, biochips have been designed for two-dimensional electrophoresis, transcriptome analysis, and PCR amplification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Other applications include various electrophoresis and liquid chromatography applications for proteins and DNA, cell separation, in particular, blood cell separation, protein analysis, cell manipulation and analysis including cell viability analysis and microorganism capturing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] By combining microfluidics with landscape ecology and nanofluidics, a nano/micro fabricated fluidic landscape can be constructed by building local patches of bacterial habitat and connecting them by dispersal corridors.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The resulting landscapes can be used as physical implementations of an adaptive landscape, by generating a spatial mosaic of patches of opportunity distributed in space and time.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The patchy nature of these fluidic landscapes allows for the study of adapting bacterial cells in a metapopulation system.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The evolutionary ecology of these bacterial systems in these synthetic ecosystems allows for using biophysics to address questions in evolutionary biology.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The ability to create precise and carefully controlled chemoattractant gradients makes microfluidics the ideal tool to study motility, chemotaxis and the ability to evolve / develop resistance to antibiotics in small populations of microorganisms and in a short period of time.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] These microorganisms including bacteria and the broad range of organisms that form the marine microbial loop, responsible for regulating much of the oceans' biogeochemistry.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidics has also greatly aided the study of durotaxis by facilitating the creation of durotactic (stiffness) gradients.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] By rectifying the motion of individual swimming bacteria, microfluidic structures can be used to extract mechanical motion from a population of motile bacterial cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This way, bacteria-powered rotors can be built.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The merger of microfluidics and optics is typical known as optofluidics.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Examples of optofluidic devices are tunable microlens arrays and optofluidic microscopes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic flow enables fast sample throughput, automated imaging of large sample populations, as well as 3D capabilities, or superresolution.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Due to the increase in safety concerns and operating costs of common analytic methods (ICP-MS, ICP-AAS, and ICP-OES), the Photonics Lab on a Chip (PhLOC) is becoming an increasingly popular tool for the analysis of actinides and nitrates in spent nuclear waste.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The PhLOC is based on the simultaneous application of Raman and UV-Vis-NIR spectroscopy, which allows for the analysis of more complex mixtures which contain several actinides at different oxidation states.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Measurements made with these methods have been validated at the bulk level for industrial tests, and are observed to have a much lower variance at the micro-scale.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This approach has been found to have molar extinction coefficients (UV-Vis) in line with known literature values over a comparatively large concentration span for 150 μL via elongation of the measurement channel, and obeys Beer's Law at the micro-scale for U(IV).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Through the development of a spectrophotometric approach to analyzing spent fuel, an on-line method for measurement of reactant quantities is created, increasing the rate at which samples can be analyzed and thus decreasing the size of deviations detectable within reprocessing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Through the application of the PhLOC, flexibility and safety of operational methods are increased.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Through the usage of fiber optic coupling, the device can be isolated from instrumentation, preventing irradiative damage and minimizing the exposure of lab personnel to potentially harmful radiation, something not possible on the lab scale nor with the previous standard of analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The shrinkage of the device also allows for lower amounts of analyte to be used, decreasing the amount of waste generated and exposure to hazardous materials.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Expansion of the PhLOC to miniaturize research of the full nuclear fuel cycle is currently being evaluated, with steps of the PUREX process successfully being demonstrated at the micro-scale.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Likewise, the microfluidic technology developed for the analysis of spent nuclear fuel is predicted to expand horizontally to analysis of other actinide, lanthanides, and transition metals with little to no modification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] High Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC) in the field of microfluidics comes in two different forms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Early designs included running liquid through the HPLC column then transferring the eluted liquid to microfluidic chips and attaching HPLC columns to the microfluidic chip directly.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The early methods had the advantage of easier detection from certain machines like those that measure fluorescence.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] HPLC columns have been integrated into microfluidic chips.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The main advantage of integrating HPLC columns into microfluidic devices is the smaller form factor that can be achieved, which allows for additional features to be combined within one microfluidic chip.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Integrated chips can also be fabricated from multiple different materials, including glass and polyimide which are quite different from the standard material of PDMS used in many different droplet-based microfluidic devices.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This is an important feature because different applications of HPLC microfluidic chips may call for different pressures.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] PDMS fails in comparison for high-pressure uses compared to glass and polyimide.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] High versatility of HPLC integration ensures robustness by avoiding connections and fittings between the column and chip.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The ability to build off said designs in the future allows the field of microfluidics to continue expanding its potential applications.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The potential applications surrounding integrated HPLC columns within microfluidic devices have proven expansive over the last 10–15 years.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The integration of such columns allows for experiments to be run where materials were in low availability or very expensive, like in biological analysis of proteins.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This reduction in reagent volumes allows for new experiments like single-cell protein analysis, which due to size limitations of prior devices, previously came with great difficulty.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The coupling of HPLC-chip devices with other spectrometry methods like mass-spectrometry allow for enhanced confidence in identification of desired species, like proteins.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic chips have also been created with internal delay-lines that allow for gradient generation to further improve HPLC, which can reduce the need for further separations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Some other practical applications of integrated HPLC chips include the determination of drug presence in a person through their hair and the labeling of peptides through reverse phase liquid chromatography.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Acoustic droplet ejection (ADE) uses a pulse of ultrasound to move low volumes of fluids (typically nanoliters or picoliters) without any physical contact.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This technology focuses acoustic energy into a fluid sample to eject droplets as small as a millionth of a millionth of a litre (picoliter = 10−12 litre).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] ADE technology is a very gentle process, and it can be used to transfer proteins, high molecular weight DNA and live cells without damage or loss of viability.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This feature makes the technology suitable for a wide variety of applications including proteomics and cell-based assays.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic fuel cells can use laminar flow to separate the fuel and its oxidant to control the interaction of the two fluids without the physical barrier that conventional fuel cells require.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] To understand the prospects for life to exist elsewhere in the universe, astrobiologists are interested in measuring the chemical composition of extraplanetary bodies.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Because of their small size and wide-ranging functionality, microfluidic devices are uniquely suited for these remote sample analyses.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] From an extraterrestrial sample, the organic content can be assessed using microchip capillary electrophoresis and selective fluorescent dyes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] These devices are capable of detecting amino acids, peptides, fatty acids, and simple aldehydes, ketones, and thiols.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] These analyses coupled together could allow powerful detection of the key components of life, and hopefully inform our search for functioning extraterrestrial life.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic techniques such as droplet microfluidics, paper microfluidics, and lab-on-a-chip are used in the realm of food science in a variety of categories.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Research in nutrition, food processing, and food safety benefit from microfluidic technique because experiments can be done with less reagents.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Food processing requires the ability to enable shelf stability in foods, such as emulsions or additions of preservatives.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Techniques such as droplet microfluidics are used to create emulsions that are more controlled and complex than those created by traditional homogenization due to the precision of droplets that is achievable.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Using microfluidics for emulsions is also more energy efficient compared to homogenization in which "only 5% of the supplied energy is used to generate the emulsion, with the rest dissipated as heat" .
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Although these methods have benefits, they currently lack the ability to be produced at large scale that is needed for commercialization.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidics are also used in research as they allow for innovation in food chemistry and food processing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] An example in food engineering research is a novel micro-3D-printed device fabricated to research production of droplets for potential food processing industry use, particularly in work with enhancing emulsions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Paper and droplet microfluidics allow for devices that can detect small amounts of unwanted bacteria or chemicals, making them useful in food safety and analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Paper-based microfluidic devices are often referred to as microfluidic paper-based analytical devices (μPADs) and can detect such things as nitrate, preservatives, or antibiotics in meat by a colorimetric reaction that can be detected with a smartphone.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] These methods are being researched because they use less reactants, space, and time compared to traditional techniques such as liquid chromatography. μPADs also make home detection tests possible, which is of interest to those with allergies and intolerances.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In addition to paper-based methods, research demonstrates droplet-based microfluidics shows promise in drastically shortening the time necessary to confirm viable bacterial contamination in agricultural waters in the domestic and international food industry.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Personalized cancer treatment is a tuned method based on the patient's diagnosis and background.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic technology offers sensitive detection with higher throughput, as well as reduced time and costs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] For personalized cancer treatment, tumor composition and drug sensitivities are very important.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] A patient's drug response can be predicted based on the status of biomarkers, or the severity and progression of the disease can be predicted based on the atypical presence of specific cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Drop-qPCR is a droplet microfluidic technology in which droplets are transported in a reusable capillary and alternately flow through two areas maintained at different constant temperatures and fluorescence detection.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] It can be efficient with a low contamination risk to detect Her2.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] A digital droplet‐based PCR method can be used to detect the KRAS mutations with TaqMan probes, to enhance detection of the mutative gene ratio.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] In addition, accurate prediction of postoperative disease progression in breast or prostate cancer patients is essential for determining post-surgery treatment.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] A simple microfluidic chamber, coated with a carefully formulated extracellular matrix mixture is used for cells obtained from tumor biopsy after 72 hours of growth and a thorough evaluation of cells by imaging.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidics is also suitable for circulating tumor cells (CTCs) and non-CTCs liquid biopsy analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Beads conjugate to anti‐epithelial cell adhesion molecule (EpCAM) antibodies for positive selection in the CTCs isolation chip (iCHIP).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] CTCs can also be detected by using the acidification of the tumor microenvironment and the difference in membrane capacitance.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] CTCs are isolated from blood by a microfluidic device, and are cultured on-chip, which can be a method to capture more biological information in a single analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] For example, it can be used to test the cell survival rate of 40 different drugs or drug combinations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Tumor‐derived extracellular vesicles can be isolated from urine and detected by an integrated double‐filtration microfluidic device; they also can be isolated from blood and detected by electrochemical sensing method with a two‐level amplification enzymatic assay.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Tumor materials can directly be used for detection through microfluidic devices.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] To screen primary cells for drugs, it is often necessary to distinguish cancerous cells from non-cancerous cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] A microfluidic chip based on the capacity of cells to pass small constrictions can sort the cell types, metastases.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Droplet‐based microfluidic devices have the potential to screen different drugs or combinations of drugs, directly on the primary tumor sample with high accuracy.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] To improve this strategy, the microfluidic program with a sequential manner of drug cocktails, coupled with fluorescent barcodes, is more efficient.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Another advanced strategy is detecting growth rates of single-cell by using suspended microchannel resonators, which can predict drug sensitivities of rare CTCs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidics devices also can simulate the tumor microenvironment, to help to test anticancer drugs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Microfluidic devices with 2D or 3D cell cultures can be used to analyze spheroids for different cancer systems (such as lung cancer and ovarian cancer), and are essential for multiple anti-cancer drugs and toxicity tests.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This strategy can be improved by increasing the throughput and production of spheroids.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] For example, one droplet-based microfluidic device for 3D cell culture produces 500 spheroids per chip.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] These spheroids can be cultured longer in different surroundings to analyze and monitor.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The other advanced technology is organs‐on‐a‐chip, and it can be used to simulate several organs to determine the drug metabolism and activity based on vessels mimicking, as well as mimic pH, oxygen... to analyze the relationship between drugs and human organ surroundings.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Other than medical and biological applications, microfluidics has been used for pollution detection and control.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Although microfluidics is exclusively used for micron-sized particles, a novel lab-on-a-chip that integrates nano-sized particle aggregation with spiral inertial microfluidics for rapid detection of nanoplastics and very small microplastics from the environment.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] One significant advancement in the field is the development of integrated capillary electrophoresis (CE) systems on microchips, as demonstrated by Z.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] They created a planar glass chip incorporating a sample injector and separation channels using micromachining techniques.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] This setup allowed for the rapid separation of amino acids in just a few seconds, achieving high separation efficiencies with up to 6800 theoretical plates.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] The use of high electric fields, possible due to the thermal mass and conductivity of glass, minimized Joule heating effects, making the system highly efficient and fast.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/microfluidics] Such innovations highlight the potential of microfluidic devices in analytical chemistry, particularly in applications requiring quick and precise analyses.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] A typical human cell contains about 2 x 3.3 billion base pairs of DNA and 600 million mRNA bases.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Usually, a mix of millions of cells is used in sequencing the DNA or RNA using traditional methods like Sanger sequencing or next generation sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] By deep sequencing of DNA and RNA from a single cell, cellular functions can be investigated extensively.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Like typical next-generation sequencing experiments, single-cell sequencing protocols generally contain the following steps: isolation of a single cell, nucleic acid extraction and amplification, sequencing library preparation, sequencing, and bioinformatic data analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] It is more challenging to perform single-cell sequencing than sequencing from cells in bulk.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The minimal amount of starting materials from a single cell makes degradation, sample loss, and contamination exert pronounced effects on the quality of sequencing data.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In addition, due to the picogram level of the number of nucleic acids used, heavy amplification is often needed during sample preparation of single-cell sequencing, resulting in uneven coverage, noise, and inaccurate quantification of sequencing data.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Recent technical improvements make single-cell sequencing a promising tool for approaching a set of seemingly inaccessible problems.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] For example, heterogeneous samples, rare cell types, cell lineage relationships, mosaicism of somatic tissues, analyses of microbes that cannot be cultured, and disease evolution can all be elucidated through single-cell sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell sequencing was selected as the method of the year 2013 by Nature Publishing Group.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell DNA genome sequencing involves isolating a single cell, amplifying the whole genome or region of interest, constructing sequencing libraries, and then applying next-generation DNA sequencing (for example Illumina, Ion Torrent).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell DNA sequencing has been widely applied in mammalian systems to study normal physiology and disease.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell resolution can uncover the roles of genetic mosaicism or intra-tumor genetic heterogeneity in cancer development or treatment response.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In the context of microbiomes, a genome from a single unicellular organism is referred to as a single amplified genome (SAG).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Advancements in single-cell DNA sequencing have enabled collecting of genomic data from uncultivated prokaryotic species present in complex microbiomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Although SAGs are characterized by low completeness and significant bias, recent computational advances have achieved the assembly of near-complete genomes from composite SAGs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Data obtained from microorganisms might establish processes for culturing in the future.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Some of the genome assembly tools used in single cell single-cell sequencing include SPAdes, IDBA-UD, Cortex, and HyDA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] A list of more than 100 different single-cell omics methods has been published.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Multiple displacement amplification (MDA) is a widely used technique, enabling amplifying femtograms of DNA from bacterium to micrograms for sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Reagents required for MDA reactions include: random primers and DNA polymerase from bacteriophage phi29.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In 30 degree isothermal reaction, DNA is amplified with included reagents.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] As the polymerases manufacture new strands, a strand displacement reaction takes place, synthesizing multiple copies from each template DNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] At the same time, the strands that were extended antecedently will be displaced.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] MDA products result in a length of about 12 kb and ranges up to around 100 kb, enabling its use in DNA sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In 2017, a major improvement to this technique, called WGA-X, was introduced by taking advantage of a thermostable mutant of the phi29 polymerase, leading to better genome recovery from individual cells, in particular those with high G+C content.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] MDA has also been implemented in a microfluidic droplet-based system to achieve a highly parallelized single-cell whole genome amplification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] By encapsulating single-cells in droplets for DNA capture and amplification, this method offers reduced bias and enhanced throughput compared to conventional MDA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] As done in MDA, this method begins with isothermal amplification, but the primers are flanked with a "common" sequence for downstream PCR amplification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] As the preliminary amplicons are generated, the common sequence promotes self-ligation and the formation of "loops" to prevent further amplification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In contrast with MDA, the highly branched DNA network is not formed.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Instead, the loops are denatured in another temperature cycle allowing the fragments to be amplified with PCR.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] MALBAC has also been implemented in a microfluidic device, but the amplification performance was not significantly improved by encapsulation in nanoliter droplets.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Comparing MDA and MALBAC, MDA results in better genome coverage, but MALBAC provides more even coverage across the genome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] MDA could be more effective for identifying SNPs, whereas MALBAC is preferred for detecting copy number variants.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] While performing MDA with a microfluidic device markedly reduces bias and contamination, the chemistry involved in MALBAC does not demonstrate the same potential for improved efficiency.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] A method particularly suitable for the discovery of genomic structural variation is Single-cell DNA template strand sequencing (a.k.a.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Using the principle of single-cell tri-channel processing, which uses joint modelling of read-orientation, read-depth, and haplotype-phase, Strand-seq enables discovery of the full spectrum of somatic structural variation classes ≥200kb in size.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The choice of method depends on the goal of the sequencing because each method presents different advantages.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] MDA of individual cell genomes results in highly uneven genome coverage, i.e. relative overrepresentation and underrepresentation of various regions of the template, leading to loss of some sequences.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] There are two components to this process: a) stochastic over- and under-amplification of random regions; and b) systematic bias against high %GC regions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The stochastic component may be addressed by pooling single-cell MDA reactions from the same cell type, by employing fluorescent in situ hybridization (FISH) and/or post-sequencing confirmation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The bias of MDA against high %GC regions can be addressed by using thermostable polymerases, such as in the process called WGA-X.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), which are a big part of genetic variation in the human genome, and copy number variation (CNV), pose problems in single cell sequencing, as well as the limited amount of DNA extracted from a single cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Due to scant amounts of DNA, accurate analysis of DNA poses problems even after amplification since coverage is low and is susceptible to errors.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] With MDA, average genome coverage is less than 80% and SNPs that are not covered by sequencing reads will be opted out.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In addition, MDA shows a high ratio of allele dropout, not detecting alleles from heterozygous samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Various SNP algorithms are currently in use but none are specific to single-cell sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] MDA with CNV also poses the problem of identifying false CNVs that conceal the real CNVs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] To solve this, when patterns can be generated from false CNVs, algorithms can detect and eradicate this noise to produce true variants.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] As a current limitation, Strand-seq requires dividing cells for strand-specific labelling using bromodeoxyuridine (BrdU), and the method does not detect variants smaller than 200kb in size, such as mobile element insertions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Microbiomes are among the main targets of single cell genomics due to the difficulty of culturing the majority of microorganisms in most environments.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell genomics is a powerful way to obtain microbial genome sequences without cultivation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This approach has been widely applied on marine, soil, subsurface, organismal, and other types of microbiomes in order to address a wide array of questions related to microbial ecology, evolution, public health and biotechnology potential.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Cancer sequencing is also an emerging application of scDNAseq.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Fresh or frozen tumors may be analyzed and categorized with respect to SCNAs, SNVs, and rearrangements quite well using whole-genome DNAS approaches.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Such overlap may provide redundancy of pathway activation and tumor cell resistance.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell DNA methylome sequencing quantifies DNA methylation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] There are several known types of methylation that occur in nature, including 5-methylcytosine (5mC), 5-hydroxymethylcytosine (5hmC), 6-methyladenosine (6mA), and 4-methylcytosine (4mC).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In eukaryotes, especially animals, 5mC is widespread along the genome and plays an important role in regulating gene expression by repressing transposable elements.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Sequencing 5mC in individual cells can reveal how epigenetic changes across genetically identical cells from a single tissue or population give rise to cells with different phenotypes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Bisulfite sequencing has become the gold standard in detecting and sequencing 5mC in single cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Treatment of DNA with bisulfite converts cytosine residues to uracil, but leaves 5-methylcytosine residues unaffected.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Therefore, DNA that has been treated with bisulfite retains only methylated cytosines.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] To obtain the methylome readout, the bisulfite-treated sequence is aligned to an unmodified genome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Whole genome bisulfite sequencing was achieved in single cells in 2014.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The method overcomes the loss of DNA associated with the typical procedure, where sequencing adapters are added prior to bisulfite fragmentation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Instead, the adapters are added after the DNA is treated and fragmented with bisulfite, allowing all fragments to be amplified by PCR.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Using deep sequencing, this method captures ~40% of the total CpGs in each cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] With existing technology DNA cannot be amplified prior to bisulfite treatment, as the 5mC marks will not be copied by the polymerase.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell reduced representation bisulfite sequencing (scRRBS) is another method.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This method leverages the tendency of methylated cytosines to cluster at CpG islands (CGIs) to enrich for areas of the genome with a high CpG content.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This reduces the cost of sequencing compared to whole-genome bisulfite sequencing, but limits the coverage of this method.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] When RRBS is applied to bulk samples, the majority of the CpG sites in gene promoters are detected, but site in gene promoters only account for 10% of CpG sites in the entire genome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In single cells, 40% of the CpG sites from the bulk sample are detected.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] To increase coverage, this method can also be applied to a small pool of single cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In a sample of 20 pooled single cells, 63% of the CpG sites from the bulk sample were detected.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Pooling single cells is one strategy to increase methylome coverage, but at the cost of obscuring the heterogeneity in the population of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] While bisulfite sequencing remains the most widely used approach for 5mC detection, the chemical treatment is harsh and fragments and degrades the DNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This effect is exacerbated when moving from bulk samples to single cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Other methods to detect DNA methylation include methylation-sensitive restriction enzymes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Restriction enzymes also enable the detection of other types of methylation, such as 6mA with DpnI.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Nanopore-based sequencing also offers a route for direct methylation sequencing without fragmentation or modification to the original DNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Nanopore sequencing has been used to sequence the methylomes of bacteria, which are dominated by 6mA and 4mC (as opposed to 5mC in eukaryotes), but this technique has not yet been scaled down to single cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell DNA methylation sequencing has been widely used to explore epigenetic differences in genetically similar cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] To validate these methods during their development, the single-cell methylome data of a mixed population were successfully classified by hierarchal clustering to identify distinct cell types.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Another application is studying single cells during the first few cell divisions in early development to understand how different cell types emerge from a single embryo.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell whole-genome bisulfite sequencing has also been used to study rare but highly active cell types in cancer such as circulating tumor cells (CTCs).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single cell transposase-accessible chromatin sequencing maps chromatin accessibility across the genome.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] A transposase inserts sequencing adapters directly into open regions of chromatin, allowing those regions to be amplified and sequenced.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The two methods for library preparation in scATAC-Seq are based on split-pool cellular indexing and microfluidics.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Standard methods such as microarrays and bulk RNA-seq analyze the RNA expression from large populations of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] These measurements may obscure critical differences between individual cells in mixed-cell populations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) provides the expression profiles of individual cells and is considered the gold standard for defining cell states and phenotypes as of 2020.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Although it is impossible to obtain complete information on every RNA expressed by each cell, due to the small amount of material available, gene expression patterns can be identified through gene clustering analyses.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This can uncover rare cell types within a cell population that may never have been seen before.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] For example, one group of scientists performing scRNA-seq on neuroblastoma tumor tissue identified a rare pan-neuroblastoma cancer cell, which may be attractive for novel therapy approaches.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Current scRNA-seq protocols involve isolating single cells and their RNA, and then following the same steps as bulk RNA-seq: reverse transcription (RT), amplification, library generation and sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Early methods separated individual cells into separate wells; more recent methods encapsulate individual cells in droplets in a microfluidic device, where the reverse transcription reaction takes place, converting RNAs to cDNAs.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Each droplet carries a DNA "barcode" that uniquely labels the cDNAs derived from a single cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Once reverse transcription is complete, the cDNAs from many cells can be mixed together for sequencing, because transcripts from a particular cell are identified by the unique barcode.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Challenges for scRNA-Seq include preserving the initial relative abundance of mRNA in a cell and identifying rare transcripts.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The reverse transcription step is critical as the efficiency of the RT reaction determines how much of the cell's RNA population will be eventually analyzed by the sequencer.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The processivity of reverse transcriptases and the priming strategies used may affect full-length cDNA production and the generation of libraries biased toward 3' or 5' end of genes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In the amplification step, either PCR or in vitro transcription (IVT) is currently used to amplify cDNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] One of the advantages of PCR-based methods is the ability to generate full-length cDNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] However, different PCR efficiency on particular sequences (for instance, GC content and snapback structure) may also be exponentially amplified, producing libraries with uneven coverage.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] On the other hand, while libraries generated by IVT can avoid PCR-induced sequence bias, specific sequences may be transcribed inefficiently, thus causing sequence drop-out or generating incomplete sequences.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Several scRNA-seq protocols have been published: Tang et al., STRT, SMART-seq, SORT-seq, CEL-seq, RAGE-seq, Quartz-seq. , and C1-CAGE.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] These protocols differ in terms of strategies for reverse transcription, cDNA synthesis and amplification, and the possibility to accommodate sequence-specific barcodes (i.e., UMIs) or the ability to process pooled samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In 2017, two approaches were introduced to simultaneously measure single-cell mRNA and protein expression through oligonucleotide-labeled antibodies known as REAP-seq, and CITE-seq.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Collecting cellular contents following electrophysiological recording using patch-clamp has also allowed development of the Patch-Seq method, which is steadily gaining ground in neuroscience.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This platform of single cell RNA sequencing allows to analyze transcriptomes on a cell-by-cell basis by the use of microfluidic partitioning to capture single cells and prepare next-generation sequencing (NGS) cDNA libraries.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The droplets based platform enables massively parallel sequencing of mRNA in a large numbers of individual cells by capturing single cell in oil droplet.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Overall, in a first stage individual cells are captured separately and lysed, then reverse transcription (RT) of mRNA is performed and cDNA library is obtained.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] To select mRNA, the RT is performed with a single-stranded sequence of deoxythymine (oligo dT) primer which bind specifically the poly(A) tail of mRNA molecules.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Subsequently, the amplified cDNA library is used for sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] So, the first step of the method is the single cell encapsulation and library preparation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Cells are encapsulated into Gel Beads-in-emulsion (GEMs) thanks to an automate.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] To form these vesicle, the automate uses a microfluidic chip and combines all components with oil.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Each functional GEM contains a single cell, a single Gel Bead, and RT reagents.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] On the Gel Bead, olignonucleotides composed by 4 distincts parts are bound: PCR primer (essential for the sequencing); 10X barcoded oligonucleotides; Unique Molecular Identifier (UMI) sequence; PolydT sequence (that enables capture of poly-adenylated mRNA molecules).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Within each GEM reaction vesicle, a single cell is lysed and undergo reverse transcription. cDNA from the same cell are identified thanks to a common 10X barcode.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In addition, the number of UMIs express the gene expression level and its analyse allows to detect highly variable genes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Those data are often used for either cellular phenotype classification or new subpopulation identification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The final step of the platform is the sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Libraries generated can be directly used for single cell whole transcriptome sequencing or target sequencing workflows.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The sequencing is performed by using the Illumina dye sequencing method.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This sequencing method is based on sequencing by synthesis (SBS) principle and the use of reversible dye-terminator that enables the identification of each single nucleotid.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In order to read the transcript sequences on one end, and the barcode and UMI on the other end, paired-end sequencing readers are required.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The droplet-based platform allows the detection of rare cell types thanks to its high throughput.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In fact, 500 to 20,000 cells are captured per sample from a single cell suspension.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The protocol is performed easily and allows a high cell recovery rate of up to 65%.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The global workflow of the droplet-based platform takes 8 hours and so is faster than the Microwell-based method (BD Rhapsody), which takes 10 hours.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] However, it presents some limitations as the need of fresh samples and the final detection of only 10% mRNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The major difference between the droplet-based method and the microwell-based method is the technique used for partitioning cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Most RNA-seq methods depend on poly(A) tail capture to enrich mRNA and deplete abundant and uninformative rRNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Thus, they are often restricted to sequencing polyadenylated mRNA molecules.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] However, recent studies are now starting to appreciate the importance of non-poly(A) RNA, such as long-noncoding RNA and microRNAs in gene expression regulation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Small-seq is a single-cell method that captures small RNAs (<300 nucleotides) such as microRNAs, fragments of tRNAs and small nucleolar RNAs in mammalian cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] This method uses a combination of "oligonucleotide masks" (that inhibit the capture of highly abundant 5.8S rRNA molecules) and size selection to exclude large RNA species such as other highly abundant rRNA molecules.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] To target larger non-poly(A) RNAs, such as long non-coding mRNA, histone mRNA, circular RNA, and enhancer RNA, size selection is not applicable for depleting the highly abundant ribosomal RNA molecules (18S and 28s rRNA).
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell RamDA-Seq is a method that achieves this by performing reverse transcription with random priming (random displacement amplification) in the presence of "not so random" (NSR) primers specifically designed to avoid priming on rRNA molecule.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] While this method successfully captures full-length total RNA transcripts for sequencing and detected a variety of non-poly(A) RNAs with high sensitivity, it has some limitations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The NSR primers were carefully designed according to rRNA sequences in the specific organism (mouse), and designing new primer sets for other species would take considerable effort.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Recently, a CRISPR-based method named scDASH (single-cell depletion of abundant sequences by hybridization) demonstrated another approach to depleting rRNA sequences from single-cell total RNA-seq libraries.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Bacteria and other prokaryotes are currently not amenable to single-cell RNA-seq due to the lack of polyadenylated mRNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Thus, the development of single-cell RNA-seq methods that do not depend on poly(A) tail capture will also be instrumental in enabling single-cell resolution microbiome studies.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Bulk bacterial studies typically apply general rRNA depletion to overcome the lack of polyadenylated mRNA on bacteria, but at the single-cell level, the total RNA found in one cell is too small.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Lack of polyadenylated mRNA and scarcity of total RNA found in single bacteria cells are two important barriers limiting the deployment of scRNA-seq in bacteria.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Limitations due to partial and biased scRNA-seq sampling also arise as scRNA-seq only captures a snap shot of cellular activity.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] For example, in large, ramified cell types like neurons, single-cell isolation only captures RNA from the central cell bodies separated from their processes during trituration.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In the brain it is estimated that over 40% of total RNA is in cellular processes such as axons, dendrites, astrocyte end-feet, and thus not visible to scRNA-seq methods.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] scRNA-Seq is becoming widely used across biological disciplines including Developmental biology, Neurology, Oncology, Immunology, Cardiovascular research, brain disease, and Infectious disease.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Using machine learning methods, data from bulk RNA-Seq has been used to increase the signal/noise ratio in scRNA-Seq.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Some scRNA-seq methods have also been applied to single cell microorganisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] SMART-seq2 has been used to analyze single cell eukaryotic microbes, but since it relies on poly(A) tail capture, it has not been applied in prokaryotic cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Microfluidic approaches such as Drop-seq and the Fluidigm IFC-C1 devices have been used to sequence single malaria parasites or single yeast cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The single-cell yeast study sought to characterize the heterogeneous stress tolerance in isogenic yeast cells before and after the yeast are exposed to salt stress.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell analysis of the several transcription factors by scRNA-seq revealed heterogeneity across the population.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] These results suggest that regulation varies among members of a population to increase the chances of survival for a fraction of the population.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The first single-cell transcriptome analysis in a prokaryotic species was accomplished using the terminator exonuclease enzyme to selectively degrade rRNA and rolling circle amplification (RCA) of mRNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In this method, the ends of single-stranded DNA were ligated together to form a circle, and the resulting loop was then used as a template for linear RNA amplification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The final product library was then analyzed by microarray, with low bias and good coverage.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] However, RCA has not been tested with RNA-seq, which typically employs next-generation sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell RNA-seq for bacteria would be highly useful for studying microbiomes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] It would address issues encountered in conventional bulk metatranscriptomics approaches, such as failing to capture species present in low abundance, and failing to resolve heterogeneity among cell populations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] scRNA-Seq has provided considerable insight into the development of embryos and organisms, including the worm Caenorhabditis elegans, and the regenerative planarian Schmidtea mediterranea and axolotl Ambystoma mexicanum.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The first vertebrate animals to be mapped in this way were Zebrafish and *Xenopus laevis*.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] In each case multiple stages of the embryo were studied, allowing the entire process of development to be mapped on a cell-by-cell basis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Science recognized these advances as the 2018 Breakthrough of the Year.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] There are several ways to isolate individual cells prior to whole genome amplification and sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Fluorescence-activated cell sorting (FACS) is a widely used approach.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Individual cells can also be collected by micromanipulation, for example by serial dilution or by using a patch pipette or nanotube to harvest a single cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The advantages of micromanipulation are ease and low cost, but they are laborious and susceptible to misidentification of cell types under microscope.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Laser-capture microdissection (LCM) can also be used for collecting single cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Although LCM preserves the knowledge of the spatial location of a sampled cell within a tissue, it is hard to capture a whole single cell without also collecting the materials from neighboring cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] High-throughput methods for single cell isolation also include microfluidics.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Both FACS and microfluidics are accurate, automatic and capable of isolating unbiased samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] However, both methods require detaching cells from their microenvironments first, thereby causing perturbation to the transcriptional profiles in RNA expression analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] The single-cell RNA-Seq protocols vary in efficiency of RNA capture, which results in differences in the number of transcripts generated from each single cell.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Single-cell libraries are usually sequenced to a depth of 1,000,000 reads because a large majority of genes are detected with 500,000 reads.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Increasing the number of cells and decreasing the read depth increases the power of identifying major cell populations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] However, low read depths may not always provide necessary information about the genes, and the difference in their expression between the cell populations is dependent on the stability and detection of the mRNA molecules.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] Quality control covariates serve as a strategy to analyze the number of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-sequencing] These covariates mainly include filtering based on count depth, the number of genes, and the fraction of counts from mitochondrial genes, which leads to the interpretation of cellular signals.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The development of high-throughput RNA sequencing (RNA-seq) and microarrays has made gene expression analysis a routine.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] RNA analysis was previously limited to tracing individual transcripts by Northern blots or quantitative PCR.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Higher throughput and speed allow researchers to frequently characterize the expression profiles of populations of thousands of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The data from bulk assays has led to identifying genes differentially expressed in distinct cell populations, and biomarker discovery.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] These studies are limited as they provide measurements for whole tissues and, as a result, show an average expression profile for all the constituent cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Firstly, different cell types within the same tissue can have distinct roles in multicellular organisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] They often form subpopulations with unique transcriptional profiles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Correlations in the gene expression of the subpopulations can often be missed due to the lack of subpopulation identification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Secondly, bulk assays fail to recognize whether a change in the expression profile is due to a change in regulation or composition — for example if one cell type arises to dominate the population.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Lastly, when one's goal is to study cellular progression through differentiation, average expression profiles can only order cells by time rather than by developmental stage.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Consequently, they cannot show trends in gene expression levels specific to certain stages.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Recent advances in biotechnology allow the measurement of gene expression in hundreds to thousands of individual cells simultaneously.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] While these breakthroughs in transcriptomics technologies have enabled the generation of single-cell transcriptomic data, they also presented new computational and analytical challenges.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Bioinformaticians can use techniques from bulk RNA-seq for single-cell data.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Still, many new computational approaches have had to be designed for this data type to facilitate a complete and detailed study of single-cell expression profiles.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] There is so far no standardized technique to generate single-cell data: all methods must include cell isolation from the population, lysate formation, amplification through reverse transcription, and quantification of expression levels.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Common techniques for measuring expression are quantitative PCR or RNA-seq.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Several methods are available to isolate and amplify cells for single-cell analysis, differing primarily in throughput and potential for cell selection.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Low-throughput techniques, such as micropipetting, cytoplasmic aspiration, and laser capture microdissection, typically isolate hundreds of cells but enable deliberate cell selection.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] High-throughput methods allow for the rapid isolation of hundreds to tens of thousands of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Common high-throughput approaches include Fluorescence Activated Cell Sorting (FACS) and the use of microfluidic devices.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Furthermore, optimized protocols have been developed by integrating these isolation techniques directly with scRNA-seq workflows.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] For instance, combining FACS with scRNA-seq led to protocols like SORT-seq, and a list of studies utilizing SORT-seq can be found here.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Similarly, the integration of microfluidic devices with scRNA-seq has been highly optimized in protocols such as those developed by 10x Genomics.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Single cell RNA-seq techniques that rely on split-pool barcoding can uniquely label cells without requiring the isolation of individual cells, including sci-RNA-seq, SPLiT-seq, and microSPLiT.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] To measure the level of expression of each transcript qPCR can be applied.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Gene specific primers are used to amplify the corresponding gene as with regular PCR and as a result data is usually only obtained for sample sizes of less than 100 genes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The inclusion of housekeeping genes, whose expression should be constant under the conditions, is used for normalization.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The most commonly used house keeping genes include GAPDH and α-actin, although the reliability of normalization through this process is questionable as there is evidence that the level of expression can vary significantly.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Fluorescent dyes are used as reporter molecules to detect the PCR product and monitor the progress of the amplification - the increase in fluorescence intensity is proportional to the amplicon concentration.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] A plot of fluorescence vs. cycle number is made and a threshold fluorescence level is used to find cycle number at which the plot reaches this value.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The cycle number at this point is known as the threshold cycle (Ct) and is measured for each gene.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The single-cell RNA-seq technique converts a population of RNAs to a library of cDNA fragments that can be sequenced.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] In droplet-based technologies such as 10x Genomics Chromium, single cells are isolated in droplets together with beads coated with barcoded oligonucleotides.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Both cells and beads are supplied in limited amounts such that co-occupancy with multiple cells and beads is a very rare event.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Cells are lysed within the droplets, and RNAs are reverse transcribed using the barcoded oligo-dT oligonucleotides as primers.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] After reverse transcription, the emulsion is broken, releasing the barcoded cDNA from all the droplets into a single solution.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] This pooled cDNA is then prepared for sequencing via the addition of sequencing adapters and PCR amplification.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] These fragments are sequenced by high-throughput next generation sequencing techniques and the reads are mapped back to the reference genome, providing a count of the number of reads associated with each gene.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Transcripts from a particular cell are identified by each cell's unique barcode.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Normalization of RNA-Seq data accounts for cell to cell variation in the efficiencies of the cDNA library formation and sequencing.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] One method relies on the use of extrinsic RNA spike-ins that are added in equal quantities to each cell lysate and used to normalize read count by the number of reads mapped to spike-in mRNA.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Another control uses unique molecular identifiers (UMIs)-short DNA sequences (6–10nt) that are added to each cDNA before amplification and act as a bar code for each cDNA molecule.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Normalization is achieved by using the count number of unique UMIs associated with each gene to account for differences in amplification efficiency.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] A combination of both spike-ins, UMIs and other approaches have been combined to help identify artifacts during library preparation and for more accurate normalization.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] scRNA-Seq is becoming widely used across biological disciplines including Development, Neurology, Oncology, Autoimmune disease, Infectious disease., brain disease, and environmental virology.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Several scRNA-Seq protocols have been published: Tang et al., STRT, SMART-seq, CEL-seq, RAGE-seq, Quartz-seq and C1-CAGE.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] These protocols differ in terms of strategies for reverse transcription, cDNA synthesis and amplification, and the possibility to accommodate sequence-specific barcodes (i.e.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] UMIs) or the ability to process pooled samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] A 2025 review in Science reported that applying single-cell transcriptomics to microbial communities reveals functional heterogeneity within gut communities, characteristic antibiotic responses, and the dynamics of mobile genetic elements.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] "Dissecting microbial communities with single-cell transcriptome analysis".
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] scRNA-Seq has provided considerable insight into the development of embryos and organisms, including the worm *Caenorhabditis elegans*, and the regenerative planarian *Schmidtea mediterranea*.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] A problem associated with single-cell data occurs in the form of zero inflated gene expression distributions, known as technical dropouts, that are common due to low mRNA concentrations of less-expressed genes that are not captured in the reverse transcription process.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The percentage of mRNA molecules in the cell lysate that are detected is often only 10-20%.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] When using RNA spike-ins for normalization the assumption is made that the amplification and sequencing efficiencies for the endogenous and spike-in RNA are the same.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Evidence suggests that this is not the case given fundamental differences in size and features, such as the lack of a polyadenylated tail in spike-ins and therefore shorter length.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Additionally, normalization using UMIs assumes the cDNA library is sequenced to saturation, which is not always the case.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The processivity of reverse transcriptases and the priming strategies used may affect full-length cDNA production and the generation of libraries biased toward the 3' or 5' end of genes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] A further consideration when sequencing large, branched cell types, such as neurons, comes from the removal of distal processes containing local pools of RNA during the single-cell isolation process.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] In these cells, scRNA-seq datasets only capture transcript in the central cell body, omitting transcripts from RNA pools localized to cellular processes that can be involved in local translation or other RNA-mediated subcellular mechanisms.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] In the brain it has been estimated that over 40% of total RNA is not sequenced by scRNA-seq due to the prevalence of local transcriptomes in cellular processes such as axons, dendrites, myelin, and endfeet.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Insights based on single-cell data analysis assume that the input is a matrix of normalized gene expression counts, generated by the approaches outlined above, and can provide opportunities that are not obtainable by bulk.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The techniques outlined have been designed to help visualise and explore patterns in the data in order to facilitate the revelation of these three features.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Clustering allows for the formation of subgroups in the cell population.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Cells can be clustered by their transcriptomic profile in order to analyse the sub-population structure and identify rare cell types or cell subtypes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Alternatively, genes can be clustered by their expression states in order to identify covarying genes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] A combination of both clustering approaches, known as biclustering, has been used to simultaneously cluster by genes and cells to find genes that behave similarly within cell clusters.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Clustering methods applied can be K-means clustering, forming disjoint groups or Hierarchical clustering, forming nested partitions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Biclustering provides several advantages by improving the resolution of clustering.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Genes that are only informative to a subset of cells and are hence only expressed there can be identified through biclustering.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Moreover, similarly behaving genes that differentiate one cell cluster from another can be identified using this method.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Dimensionality reduction algorithms such as Principal component analysis (PCA) and t-SNE can be used to simplify data for visualisation and pattern detection by transforming cells from a high to a lower dimensional space.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The result of this method produces graphs with each cell as a point in a 2-D or 3-D space.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Dimensionality reduction is frequently used before clustering as cells in high dimensions can wrongly appear to be close due to distance metrics behaving non-intuitively.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The contribution each gene makes to each component is used to infer which genes are contributing the most to variance in the population and are involved in differentiating different subpopulations.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Detecting differences in gene expression level between two populations is used both single-cell and bulk transcriptomic data.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Specialised methods have been designed for single-cell data that considers single cell features such as technical dropouts and shape of the distribution e.g.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Gene Ontology (GO) term enrichment is a technique used to identify which GO terms are over-represented or under-represented in a given set of genes.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] In single-cell analysis input list of genes of interest can be selected based on differentially expressed genes or groups of genes generated from biclustering.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The number of genes annotated to a GO term in the input list is normalized against the number of genes annotated to a GO term in the background set of all genes in genome to determine statistical significance.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Pseudo-temporal ordering (or trajectory inference) is a technique that aims to infer gene expression dynamics from snapshot single-cell data.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The method tries to order the cells in such a way that similar cells are closely positioned to each other.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] This trajectory of cells can be linear, but can also bifurcate or follow more complex graph structures.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The trajectory, therefore, enables the inference of gene expression dynamics and the ordering of cells by their progression through differentiation or response to external stimuli.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The method relies on the assumptions that the cells follow the same path through the process of interest and that their transcriptional state correlates to their progression.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The algorithm can be applied to both mixed populations and temporal samples.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] More than 50 methods for pseudo-temporal ordering have been developed, and each has its own requirements for prior information (such as starting cells or time course data), detectable topologies, and methodology.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] An example algorithm is the Monocle algorithm that carries out dimensionality reduction of the data, builds a minimal spanning tree using the transformed data, orders cells in pseudo-time by following the longest connected path of the tree and consequently labels cells by type.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Another example is the diffusion pseudotime (DPT) algorithm, which uses a diffusion map and diffusion process.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Another class of methods such as MARGARET employ graph partitioning for capturing complex trajectory topologies such as disconnected and multifurcating trajectories.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Gene regulatory network inference is a technique that aims to construct a network, shown as a graph, in which the nodes represent the genes and edges indicate co-regulatory interactions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The method relies on the assumption that a strong statistical relationship between the expression of genes is an indication of a potential functional relationship.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The most commonly used method to measure the strength of a statistical relationship is correlation.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] However, correlation fails to identify non-linear relationships and mutual information is used as an alternative.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Gene clusters linked in a network signify genes that undergo coordinated changes in expression.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The presence or strength of technical effects and the types of cells observed often differ in single-cell transcriptomics datasets generated using different experimental protocols and under different conditions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] This difference results in strong batch effects that may bias the findings of statistical methods applied across batches, particularly in the presence of confounding.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] As a result of the aforementioned properties of single-cell transcriptomic data, batch correction methods developed for bulk sequencing data were observed to perform poorly.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Consequently, researchers developed statistical methods to correct for batch effects that are robust to the properties of single-cell transcriptomic data to integrate data from different sources or experimental batches.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Laleh Haghverdi performed foundational work in formulating the use of mutual nearest neighbors between each batch to define batch correction vectors.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] With these vectors, one can merge datasets that each include at least one shared cell type.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] An orthogonal approach involves the projection of each dataset onto a shared low-dimensional space using canonical correlation analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Mutual nearest neighbors and canonical correlation analysis have also been combined to define integration "anchors" comprising reference cells in one dataset, to which query cells in another dataset are normalized.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Cell-cell communication tools leverage the expression of cognate ligand and receptor pairs in distinct cell pairs to predict putative interactions between cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] A pioneer tool is CellPhoneDB, which included a curate database of receptor complexes and ligand-receptor interactions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] The method also implemented a statistical test by evaluating the expression of the ligand-receptor in the respective cell pair.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] One interesting advanced analysis is at scenarios when two conditions (disease vs. controls) are available.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Here, one is interested in finding cell-cell interactions specific to disease or control conditions.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] With the lowering of single cell cost, it is possible to measure single cell data over large disease cohorts with up to 100 individual samples and million of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] This brings several challenges such as individual variability and the multi-scale properties of the data, every single cell experiment represents a distribution of cells.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] MILO tackle individual variability by encoding single cell data as a k-nn graph followed by a differential abundance test.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] This allows to find cellular neighboorhoods associated to a particular disease condition.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Optimal transport theory is another represents another framework to tackle multi-scale nature of single cell diseae atlas.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] By encoding single cell experiments of an patient as a distribution of cells, optimal transport based Wasserstein distance allows to measure a distance between two patient.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] This can be used for sample level clustering and trajectory analysis as explored by PILOT and QOT.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] An important pilar of single cell analysis are software packages providing functionally for quality check, normalization, clustering and down-stream analysis described above.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] They also provide data containers for the storage and representation of analysed single cell data.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Seurat is the first and possibly most complete frameworks for single cell analysis.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Scanpy is an alternative for python language.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/single-cell-transcriptomics] Additional software package offer specific data analysis taks.
[src:single-cell-sequencing/unique-molecular-identifier] Applications include analysis of unique cDNAs to avoid PCR biases in iCLIP, variant calling in ctDNA, gene expression in single-cell RNA-seq (scRNA-seq) and haplotyping via linked reads.
